Try running with the 64bit jvm and set the jvm option
&quot;-XX:-UseGCOverheadLimit&quot;.  The issue you&#39;re having is not really an out of
memory problem but a gc problem where it thinks it&#39;s spending too much time
trying to free up memory.  See
http://java.sun.com/javase/technologies/hotspot/gc/gc_tuning_6.html#par_gc.o
om



- leo



  _____  

From: archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com
[mailto:archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com] On Behalf Of Juergen Umbrich
Sent: Thursday, October 23, 2008 11:32 AM
To: archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com
Subject: [archive-crawler] Re: Broad-scope 10M seeds Xmx6G 64-Bit JVM: OOME:
GC overhead limit exceeded



Hi all

we run another crawl. The same setup as the crawl yesterday.
This time we used a 32-Bit JVM with JAVA_OPTS=&quot; -Xmx3G&quot; , so we 
decreased the allocated memory!!!

Again after ~5h crawling the crawler slowed down and exactly the same 
exception occured.
*Frontier*
803592 URI queues: 785 active (149 in-process; 466 ready; 170 snoozed); 
801921 inactive; 0 ineligible; 0 retired; 886 exhausted [RUN: 0 in, 50 out]

It seems like bdb is the cause for this problem.
~800K queues are to much to handle with the defaul setiting..

Has anyone some suggestions how we can solve this problem without 
changing our scope??
Any other queue assignment policy?
bdb-cache-percentage:20?
using a different je-library?

best juergen

Juergen Umbrich wrote:
&gt; Hi all,
&gt;
&gt; we started yesterday evening a large crawl (10M seed URIs, 100 
&gt; threads, BloomURIUniquFilter) on a server with the following setup:
&gt; ubuntu 8.04 server, quad core XEON 2.33GHz, 8GB RAM
&gt;
&gt; and the java version
&gt; java version &quot;1.6.0_06&quot;
&gt; Java(TM) SE Runtime Environment (build 1.6.0_06-b02)
&gt; Java HotSpot(TM) 64-Bit Server VM (build 10.0-b22, mixed mode)
&gt;
&gt; Heritrix was started with the webui and JAVA_OPTS=&quot; -Xmx6G&quot;
&gt; bdb-cache-percentage:60
&gt;
&gt; after around 5 hours (timestamp 2008-10-23T01:25:12Z in 
&gt; progress-statistics.log) the whole crawling process was slowing down
&gt; and another 40 minutes later we run into a 
&gt; &quot;java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: GC overhead limit exceeded&quot; error message:
&gt; After the exepction occurred the crawling is trying to pause
&gt; The most of the toe-threads are in the state
&gt; in processor: ACTIVE for 9h17m23s171ms
&gt; step: ABOUT_TO_RETURN_URI for 9h15m21s608ms
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Anyone else run into these problems for a large crawl and a big seed set?
&gt; And any ideas how we can solve this problem? switching to 32-bit JVM?
&gt; decreasing the Xmx?
&gt; using different modules?
&gt; changing the bdb-cache-percentage to 20?
